title: For Sale:  Swiss K-31 rifle
postcontent:
Swiss 7.5x55 Straight Pull Rifles
although the K31 is a straight-pull carbine like many other Swiss rifles, it was not designed by Rudolf Schmidt (1832-1898) as he was not alive to do so. 
The K31 was a totally new design by Eidgenossische Waffenfabrik in Bern, Switzerland under Colonel Furrer, and the gun does not have the Schmidt-designed 1889 or 1896 action. The first 200 K31s were made in May 1931 for troop trials (serials 500,001 - 500,200), thus the model number of 1931
It is a shooter .One of the most accurate rifles ever made

title: For Sale/Trade:  Springfield WWII dated M1 Garand Almost Parts Correct-SPF
postcontent:
-M1 Garand, .30-06. 1943 dated receiver. I built it from a stripped receiver trying to match finishes as much as possible. The receiver has some minor pitting below the wood line that is nicely covered by the re-park. Wood is new Boyd's replacement from the CMP that I stripped off another gun that I restored for personal collection. The wood receiver fit is super. Barrel is replacement 1955 dated, but gauges 1 or less on the throat and muzzle, bore 9+/10. Most of the parts are period correct for this Garand other then: OpRod, Barrel, Wood, Hammer and follower spring arm. The rear sight is a Type II Lockbar. Comes with 2 enbloc clips. 

Asking $SPF FTF (shipped on your dime) for what is basically a CMP special grade with superior USGI barrel and most of the correct era parts. I was going to finish off with more correct parts and barrel, but this one shot well after the build I didn't want to go any further, maybe you can swap the rest of the parts out if that's you're preference. Or find the correct stock and have both a shooter and a  showpiece.

title: For Sale:  Pre-Ban Springfield Armory M1a Standard with ART IV Scope
location: Fort Bragg, Raeford, Fayetteville, Fayetteville, North Carolina
postcontent:
I've got a Springfield Armory M1a Standard in a Walnut stock with a Springfield Armory ART IV (Auto Ranging) scope mounted on a Springfield Armory Gen 3 scope mount. Rifle and scope are in great condition with very little wear shown. USGI Parts, 7.62mm stamped roll mark on the receiver.

These rifle/scope combos were sold by Springfield during the late '80s, maybe into the early '90s.
Serial # starts at 060 which makes it a 1990 manufacture date. (Pre-Ban)
Barrel marked: Winchester Trade Mark 7790190 –Sep
Bolt Marked:7790186 on the top and HRT A10 below it.

Rifle will come with one 20 round magazine.
Springfield Armory A.R.T. IV, 1-inch 3x9 variable power riflescope

ART IV Scope Background: 
. The A.R.T. IV is a superior quality variable power telescopic sighting system commercially manufactured by Buris and sold by Springfield Armory in the mid to late 1980s. 
. It is specifically applicable to all M1 Garand, M14 and M1A, BM59 and BM62, Valmet M76 and M78, SIG 510-4 and AMT, FAL, LAR, StG 58, L1A1, SAR 48, SAR 4800, SAR 8, HK91, and other rifles using the 7.62x51mm NATO/.308 Win., .30-06, and similar cartridges. 

Features: 
. Automatic range finding. 
. Automatic compensating reticle crosshair plex to maintain bullet-impact zero. 
. Calibrated for .308 Win., 168-grain bullets at 2600 fps and compensates for bullet-drop from 200 to 550 yards. 

How to Use: 
. Zero the rifle at 200 yards. 
. The two stadia lines at the bottom represent 18 inches at any distance. 
. Dial magnification until 18 inches of target fits into the two stadia lines. 
. The center horizontal crosshair splits and begins to separate. If shooting at 200 yards (at any magnification between 3x and 9x), use the top crosshair. If shooting at an unknown distance and have dialed in your stadia lines, use the bottom crosshair as it is compensating for holdover at the dialed in range.
